  "top_untranslatable_reasons": {
    "Signal requires statistical comparison of January returns vs. Feb-Dec average (dummy variable regression with OLS, p < 0.05). This is a cross-sectional statistical test not expressible using point-in-time technical indicators. The 'returns' indicator captures monthly returns but cannot encode the statistical hypothesis test (p-value comparison across month groups) or the regression methodology. The operator 'is' cannot map to a live regression calculation.": 1,
    "Calendar-based month detection (January/February) is not available in the allowed indicators list. The allowed indicators are technical (RSI, MACD, moving averages, etc.) and do not include calendar date or month extraction functions. To translate this signal, a DATE or MONTH indicator would be needed.": 1,
    "Calendar-based month filtering (January entry, avoid March/April) requires a calendar/date indicator not in the ALLOWED INDICATORS list. The operator 'is' is only defined for regime comparisons, not for calendar month matching. To implement this rule, a month() or calendar_month indicator would be required.": 1,
    "Signal relies on calendar-based month filtering (January entry/exit) and multi-index selection logic that cannot be expressed using the allowed technical indicators and operators. Month comparisons and index selection require calendar/data structure operations outside the indicator-based rule engine. The 'abnormal returns' statistical significance (p < 0.05) is a research finding, not a tradeable condition.": 1,
    "Signal requires calendar-based month filtering (Month == January) and index selection logic ([CNX Nifty, CNX Jr, CNX Midcap, CNX IT, Bank Nifty]). These are data-level filters, not technical indicators. The 'operator' is used for 'is' comparison, but the allowed indicators list does not include month/calendar fields or index identifiers. The statistical significance level (0.1) and mean January coefficient (0.01) cannot be operationalized as entry conditions without direct access to regression coefficients or statistical test results, which are not in the allowed indicators. This signal requires preprocessing at the data/asset selection layer before the backtest engine executes technical rule logic.": 1,
    "Calendar-based entry condition (Month = January) cannot be expressed using allowed indicators. The 'close' indicator represents price data, not calendar month. Allowed indicators are technical/price-based only and do not include date/month functions. A backtest engine would need explicit date filtering logic outside the indicator framework.": 1,
    "Signal requires calendar-based condition ('Date is a futures contract expiration day on NSE') and GARCH volatility framework detection, neither of which are available in the allowed indicators set. GARCH volatility cannot be directly computed from the provided indicators (hvol_20 is historical volatility, not GARCH). Approximated using india_vix and hvol_20 as volatility proxies, but this is a functional substitute rather than true GARCH-based detection.": 1,
    "Signal requires detection of 'futures_expiration_day' and 'price reversal effect' which are calendar/event-based triggers not available in the allowed indicator set. The signal also requires identifying when 'price pressure is released' which lacks a precise technical definition. A reversion-based proxy has been constructed using price direction reversal, but the core event-driven logic cannot be fully translated without a futures expiration calendar indicator.": 1,
    "Signal requires calendar-based entry (futures expiration week) and GARCH conditional variance measurement. The allowed indicator set lacks: (1) calendar/event detection for contract expiration dates, (2) GARCH model output. hvol_20 is a proxy for volatility elevation but cannot capture the specific conditional variance modeling or expiration-week timing requirement. A backtest engine would need external event data and GARCH computation to properly implement this signal.": 1,
    "Signal requires access to ARMA-GARCH model coefficients (\u03a61, \u03b21) and futures expiration day dummy variable (ExpD_t, NextD_t) which are not available in the allowed indicator list. These are econometric model parameters derived from statistical regression, not standard technical indicators. The signal logic cannot be expressed using only the allowed price-based, momentum, volatility, and volume indicators.": 1,
    "Signal requires GARCH model coefficients and futures expiration day identification which are not available in the allowed indicators list. GARCH volatility modeling, expiration day dummy variable significance testing, and statistical mean/variance level analysis cannot be expressed using only the provided technical indicators (moving averages, RSI, ATR, Bollinger Bands, MACD, etc.). The signal is fundamentally based on econometric modeling outputs rather than real-time price/volume technicals.": 1,
    "Signal requires identification of futures contract expiration day (a calendar/contract-specific event) and GARCH variance equation coefficients (0.819), which are not available in the standard technical indicator set. The backtest engine lacks: (1) expiration_day dummy variable, (2) GARCH volatility model parameters. Cannot construct precise entry conditions without these structural/statistical indicators.": 1,
    "Signal requires detection of futures contract expiration day (calendar-based event) and identification of specific affected instruments (Nifty + 17 individual stocks, excluding CIPLA, HDFC, M&M, ONGC). These require external data sources and pre-filtering logic not available in the indicator-based rule engine. The core volatility expansion can be captured via india_vix, but the expiration day trigger and stock-level filtering must be implemented at the backtest engine level as separate event handlers.": 1,
    "Signal requires detecting 'futures expiration days (ED)' as a calendar event and comparing intraday mean returns on ED vs non-ED days. The allowed indicators do not include calendar event detection, market microstructure data, or statistical aggregation of returns across ED/non-ED cohorts. The rule fundamentally depends on external calendar metadata and cross-sectional return analysis that cannot be expressed using the available price/technical indicators. A valid implementation would require: (1) a calendar data source identifying expiration dates, and (2) capability to compute conditional mean returns stratified by event type.": 1,
    "Signal requires detection of calendar event (futures expiration day) and GARCH(1,1) variance equation coefficients with statistical significance testing (p<0.01). These are NOT available in the allowed indicators list. The signal also requires pre-computed GARCH ExpD coefficients for specific stocks (ACC, BHEL, BPCL, Dr. Reddy's, GRASIM, INFOSYS, ITC). Backtest engine does not support: (1) calendar-event triggering, (2) GARCH model estimation, (3) statistical significance thresholds. Approximated with india_vix spike as volatility proxy, but this does not capture the expiration-day specific effect.": 1,
    "Signal requires detection of futures expiration day (ExpD) as a calendar event and GARCH(1,1) volatility coefficient modeling with Student-t distribution. The backtest engine lacks: (1) calendar event detection for NSE futures expiration dates, (2) GARCH model-derived volatility coefficients, (3) statistical significance testing framework at 1% level. hvol_20 is used as a proxy for elevated volatility, but cannot capture the specific ExpD effect or model-based coefficient significance documented in the empirical results.": 1,
    "Signal requires detection of GARCH model ExpD coefficient from variance equation (p < 0.01), which is an econometric parameter not available in the allowed indicator list. The signal is fundamentally based on statistical estimation from a fitted GARCH model, not on real-time price/volume indicators. hvol_20 (historical volatility) is the closest proxy but does not capture the specific ExpD coefficient significance test required by the original rule.": 1,
    "The BAB (Betting Against Beta) factor requires explicit beta calculation and leverage application across a portfolio of assets. The allowed indicators do not include beta, correlation, or leverage multipliers. The signal requires: (1) computing beta for each asset relative to a benchmark, (2) sorting assets by beta quintiles, (3) applying leverage to the low-beta leg, (4) shorting high-beta assets. These operations are portfolio-level and risk-management constructs that cannot be expressed as single-asset price/technical conditions using only the provided indicators.": 1,
    "BAB (Betting Against Beta) factor strategy requires explicit beta calculations and cross-asset beta-relative positioning that cannot be expressed using only technical price-based indicators. The strategy fundamentally requires: (1) Beta estimation per asset, (2) Leverage/de-leverage calculations to target beta=1.0, (3) Cross-sectional ranking and portfolio construction across multiple assets with correlated offsetting positions. None of the ALLOWED INDICATORS support direct beta measurement, leverage application, or multi-asset factor decomposition. This is a portfolio-level factor strategy, not a single-asset technical signal.": 1,
